import Mathlib

/-!## Definition of path in a tableau
A path in a tableaux `t` is a sequence of tableaux `t₀, t₁, ..., tₙ` such that:
- `t₀ = t`
- `tᵢ` is the initial tableaux of `tᵢ₊₁` for all `i < n`
- `tₙ` is a final tableaux
- The sequence is non-empty (i.e., `n ≥ 0`)
- We consider the empty path `[]` as the root of the tableaux tree.

For a path `p = [t₀, t₁, ..., tₙ]`, we denote:
- `p.length = n + 1` (the number of tableaux in the path)
- `p.isLoaded` is true if `tₙ` (the last tableaux) is loaded
- `p.isFinal` is true if `tₙ` (the last tableaux) is final
- `p.isLeaf` is true if `p.length = 1` (i.e., the path consists of the root tableaux)
- `p.isRoot` is true if `p = []` (the empty path)

For a path `p = [t₀, t₁, ..., tₙ]`, we define the following operations:
- `p.head`: the first tableaux `t₀`
- `p.tail`: the path `[t₁, ..., tₙ]` (if `p.length ≥ 1`)
- `p.isLoaded`: `tₙ` is loaded
- `p.isFinal`: `tₙ` is final
- `p.isLeaf`: `p.length = 1`
- `p.isRoot`: `p = []`

We also define the following relations:
- `p₁ ≺ p₂` if `p₁` is a prefix of `p₂` and `p₂.length > p₁.length`
- `p₁ ⋖ p₂` if `p₁` and `p₂` share a common prefix and their last tableaux are different
- `p₁ ≡ p₂` if `p₁` and `p₂` are the same path

We use the following notations for specific paths:
- `p.0`: the first tableaux of path `p`
- `p.1`: the second tableaux of path `p` (if length ≥ 2)
- `p[-1]`: the last tableaux of path `p` (if length ≥ 1)
- `p[-2]`: the second last tableaux of path `p` (if length ≥ 2)
- `p[0]`: the first tableaux of path `p`
- `p[1]`: the second tableaux of path `p` (if length ≥ 2)
- `p[-1]`: the last tableaux of path `p` (if length ≥ 1)
- `p[-2]`: the second last tableaux of path `p` (if length ≥ 2)

We also define the following operations on paths:
- `p.map f`: apply function `f` to each tableaux in the path
- `p.attach`: the path formed by attaching the current path to the end of another path
- `p.reverse`: the path formed by reversing the order of tableaux in `p`
- `p.succ`: the path formed by adding one more tableaux to the end of `p`

We define the following notations:
- `p₁ * p₂`: the concatenation of `p₁` and `p₂`
- `p₁ + p₂`: the sum of the lengths of `p₁` and `p₂`
- `p₁ < p₂`: the prefix relation `p₁ ≺ p₂`
- `p₁ ≤ p₂`: the relation `p₁ ≺ p₂` or `p₁ = p₂`
- `p₁ > p₂`: the relation `p₂ < p₁`
- `p₁ ≥ p₂`: the relation `p₂ ≤ p₁`
- `p₁ ≠ p₂`: the relation `¬(p₁ = p₂)`
- `p₁ ∉ S`: the relation `¬(p₁ ∈ S)` for a set `S` of paths
- `p₁ ∈ S`: the relation `p₁` is an element of the set `S`
- `p₁ ∈ p₂`: the relation `p₁` is a subpath of `p₂`
- `p₁ ∉ p₂`: the relation `¬(p₁ ∈ p₂)`
- `p₁ ∩ p₂`: the set of common prefixes of `p₁` and `p₂`
- `p₁ ∪ p₂`: the set of paths that are in `p₁` or `p₂` or both
- `p₁ \ p₂`: the set difference `{q ∈ p₁ | q ∉ p₂}`
